Be-Organized

Version Control System

   First things first, everyone should know version control systems.
   Version control is one of the most useful tools for scientists.
     * git
     * svn
     * mercurial

Online Git Service

     * [https://github.com/]GitHub: No description needed.
     * [https://bitbucket.org/]BitBucket: Alternative to GitHub with free
       private repositories for small teams (up to 5 users).
     * [http://gitlab.org/]GitLab: Similar to GitHub and BitBucket, can be
       both cloud-based and self-hosted. It includes unlimited free
       private repositories, issue tracker and a continuous integration
       tool.

Self-hosted Git Server

     * [http://gitlab.org/]GitLab: See above at
       [file://localhost/Users/admin/Pros/sh/awesome/awe_raw/awesome-resea
       rch#online-git-service]Online Git Service.
     * [https://www.gitorious.org/]Gitorious: Acquired by GitLab and
       discontinued, but [http://getgitorious.com/]the software can still
       be installed.

Enterprise Git Service

     * [https://rhodecode.com/]Rhodecode
     * [https://codeplane.com/]Codeplane

Pomodoro

   Try [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pomodoro_Technique]Pomodoro
   Technique to gain efficiency and probably health.
     * [https://pomotodo.com/]Pomotodo (Cloud,Mac,Win,Android,iOS,Chrome):
       A mix of todo list and pomodoro timer, with sync across devices and
       weekly report [Free].
     * [http://tadamapp.com/]Tadam (Mac): Simple and elegant pomodoro
       timer [USD$ 4.99].
     * [https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.wlxd.pomochallen
       ge&hl=en]Productivity Challenge Timer (Android): Pomodoro timer
       with great gamification features [Free].

GTD-Task Manager

   The GTD (Getting Things Done) method rests on the idea of moving
   planned tasks and projects out of the mind by recording them externally
   and then breaking them into actionable work items. This allows one to
   focus attention on taking action on tasks, instead of on recalling them
   ([https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Getting_Things_Done]Wikipedia). Tasks
   can be classified in contexts (@home, @computer, @office, etc), time of
   action (now, next actions, scheduled or someday) and projects.
   [https://hamberg.no/gtd/]Here we have a good pragmatic guide to GTD and
   [http://gettingthingsdone.com/pdfs/tt_workflow_chart.pdf]here a
   flowchart.
     * [https://www.wunderlist.com/]Wunderlist
       (Cloud,Mac,Win,Android,iOS,Win Store,Chrome OS): Almost perfect
       todo lists with cooperation and sharing.
     * [https://evernote.com/]Evernote (Cloud,Mac,Win,Android,iOS,Win
       Store): Not so lightweight but still very good for managing life
       especially since it has got a lot of integrations from a lot of
       other services.
     * [http://www.any.do/]Anydo (Cloud,Mac,Android,iOS): Good because it
       has a very good daily review which can help users remember what to
       do.
     * [https://todoist.com/]Todoist (Cloud,Mac,Win,Android,iOS): Todoist
       invented the karma system which keeps track of the tasks done.
     * [https://taskade.com/]Taskade (Cloud,Chrome OS,Firefox,Mobile
       coming soon,): Taskade is a collaborative task list and outliner
       for team projects.

Cloud Services

   For self-hosted services, check out
   [https://github.com/Kickball/awesome-selfhosted]awesome-selfhosted on
   GitHub.

Math and Programming

   Coding/Numerical calculation/Analytical derivation online.
     * [https://cloud.sagemath.com/]Sagemath: LaTeX, R, iPython Notebook,
       etc.
     * [http://picloud.com/]PiCloud: python, but it was acquired by
       Dropbox and has been shut down. The new site is
       [http://www.multyvac.com/]Multyvac.
     * [https://www.multyvac.com/]Multyvac: Kind of the successor of
       PiCloud but will be more powerful for sure.
     * [http://www.wolframalpha.com/]WolframAlpha: Excellent engine to do
       mathematical derivation online and search.

Plots

     * [https://plot.ly/]plot.ly: Online plotting with many cloud services
       integrated.
     * [https://www.desmos.com/calculator]Desmos: Graphs for functions.
     * [http://graph.tk/]graph.tk: Online plotting with rich features.
     * [https://www.getdatajoy.com/]DataJoy: Developed by ShareLaTeX team;
       python & R at this moment.
     * [http://www.wolframalpha.com/]Wolfram Alpha: Make graphs for
       functions, from your data and even more.

Data

   Nature hosts a list of recommended data repositories
   [http://www.nature.com/sdata/policies/repositories]here.

General and Interdisciplinary

     * [http://datadryad.org/]DRYAD (Storage, Lookup): The Dryad Digital
       Repository stores curated data.
     * [https://figshare.com/]Figshare (Storage, Lookup): Data sharing and
       storage
     * [http://data.gov/]Data.gov (Lookup): Data by US Federal Government

Life Science

     * [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genbank/]GenBank (Lookup): Genetic
       sequence database
     * [https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/]National Centers for Environmental
       Information (Lookup): Weather, climate, coasts, oceans, and
       geophysics etc
     * [http://www.geoportal.org/web/guest/geo_home_stp]GEOSS Portal
       (Lookup): Earth science data

Physical Sciences

     * [http://www.usvao.org/]US Virtual Astronomical Observatory (Lookup)
     * [https://mast.stsci.edu/portal/Mashup/Clients/Mast/portal.html]MAST
       : Barbara A. Mikulski Archive for Space Telescopes (Lookup)
     * [http://archive.stsci.edu/]Mikulski Archive for Space Telescopes
       (Lookup)

Arts and Humanities

     * [http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/]Archaeology Data Service
       (Lookup): Certified repository

Engineering

     * [http://en.openei.org/wiki/Main_Page]Open Energy Information
       (OpenEI) (Lookup): Wiki of collections of energy information

Social Sciences

     * [https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/landing.jsp]Inter-university
       Consortium for Political and Social Research (ICPSR) (Lookup)
     * [http://library.harvard.edu/gdc]Institute for Quantitative Social
       Science (IQSS) (Lookup)

Colors

   Pick a pleasing color for your presentations and notes.
     * [http://www.checkman.io/please/]PleaseJS
     * [http://colorbrewer2.org/]ColorBrewer
     * [http://paletton.com/]Paletton
     * [https://www.sessions.edu/color-calculator/]Color Calculator

Publishing and Sharing

   Make use of [http://github.com/]GitHub to cooperate with others.
   [https://pages.github.com/]GitHub pages is also good for hosting static
   contents.

Writing

   Markdown is one of the best languages for writing. Check out these
   editor in
   [file://localhost/Users/admin/Pros/sh/awesome/awe_raw/awesome-research#
   markdown]Markdown section.

   Make use of these programs for publishing:
     * [http://sphinx-doc.org/]Sphinx: RestructuredText as source files,
       powerful, flexible and modularized.
     * [https://www.gitbook.com/]Gitbook: A new but promising tool for
       HTML, pdf, and epub with both online editors and local editors.
       Plugins like quizzes and math can be helpful to writing science.
     * [https://github.com/schacon/git-scribe]Git-scribe: Good for writing
       ebooks.
     * Static Site Generator: For more please
       refer to
       [file://localhost/Users/admin/Pros/sh/awesome/awe_raw/awesome-resea
       rch#static-site-generator]Static Site Generator.

   Sphinx Themes and configurations
     * Themes
          + [https://github.com/snide/sphinx_rtd_theme]rtd theme:
            Developed by ReadtheDocs.org
          + [https://github.com/bitprophet/alabaster]Alabaster: Clean and
            simple
          + [https://github.com/vkvn/sphinx-themes]Some beautiful themes
          + [https://ryan-roemer.github.io/sphinx-bootstrap-theme/]Bootstr
            ap theme

   Science Books Using Sphinx
     * [https://github.com/certik/theoretical-physics]Theoretical Physics
     * [https://github.com/emptymalei/statisticalphysics]Statistical
       Physics
     * [https://github.com/NeuPhysics/neutrino]Neutrino Physics

Hosting

   Host your articles, notes and more.
     * [http://readthedocs.org/]ReadtheDocs: Turn your reStructuredText
       source to HTML, pdf, and epub, all done online.
     * [https://pages.github.com/]GitHub pages: Integrated with Jekyll and
       turns markdown posts automatically. Jekyll is a tool for blogging.
     * [http://github.com/]GitHub: Just put markdown, reStructuredText,
       pdf or ipython notebook files on GitHub. All these formats can be
       previewed online. The thing to mention is that the math in ipython
       notebook can be rendered on GitHub.
     * [https://www.aerobatic.com/]Aerobatic: A powerful alternative to
       GitHub Pages.
     * [https://surge.sh/]Surge: One command upload your static website to
       make it live. Surge also integrates GitHub hooks.
     * [https://www.heroku.com/]Heroku: The one that needs no
       explaination.

   Other services such as [https://www.digitalocean.com/]Digital Ocean are
   also useful when it comes to dynamic websites and cloud computing.

Blog and CMS

   Before doing the investigation on platforms, just remind yourself:

     I want to write, not to run blogging software.

   Blog/CMS Software

   These programs are running on the server and can be
   hosted using these services.
     * [https://wordpress.org/]Wordpress (PHP): Very popular but requires
       a lot of maintenance.
     * [https://github.com/tryghost/Ghost]Ghost (Node.js): Open, Simple,
       non-profit; write with markdown and live preview.
     * [https://github.com/picocms/Pico]Pico (PHP): Lightweight cms, open
       source, no database.
     * [https://github.com/circa75/dropplets]Dropplets (PHP): Open source,
       simple, and elegant blog system; write in Markdown.

   These Blog/CMS software can be hosted on
   [https://www.digitalocean.com/]Digital Ocean.

Static Site Generator

   [https://staticsitegenerators.net/]Here is a nice website that tells
   you all the static site generators. Nonethless here is a list of the
   most popular ones.
     * [http://jekyllrb.com/]Jekyll (Written in Ruby)(Markdown): Jekyll is
       the most widely used one. The best part about Jekyll is that one
       just deploy to GitHub Pages by pushing the source to GitHub.
     * [http://octopress.org/]Octopress (Written in Ruby)(Markdown):
       Octopress is easier to use compared with Jekyll while being
       somewhat compatible with Jekyll.
     * [https://hexo.io/]Hexo (Written in Node.js)(Markdown): "A fast,
       simple & powerful blog framework" as they say on their website. It
       supports GFM.
     * [http://getpelican.com/]Pelican (Written in
       Python)(reStructuredText,Markdown,AsciiDoc): Pelican is a
       modularized framework and is perfect for blogging.
          + [https://github.com/wting/pelican-svbtle]Pelican Svbtle Theme
     * [https://getnikola.com/]Nikola (Written in
       Python)(reStructuredText,Markdown,IPython Notebook/Jupyter,PHP,
       etc): It takes in multiple input formats including reStructuredText
       and many others.
     * [http://gohugo.io/]Hugo(Written in Go)(Markdown): Easy to use and
       really fast. It also supports more input formats through plugins.

   The site generated by these programs can be hosted on
   [https://pages.github.com/]GitHub Pages.

Note Taking

Editors

   Markdown, reStructuredText, and LaTeX are the three chosen languages.

Markdown

     * [https://stackedit.io/]StackEdit(Cloud): StackEdit is a Markdown
       editor with many integrated services such as math (MathJax), Google
       Drive, Dropbox, and GitHub.
     * [https://hackmd.io/]Hackmd.io (Cloud): Basically ships with
       everything you expect from the most complete online markdown
       editor.
     * [https://www.zybuluo.com/mdeditor]CMD markdown(Cloud): CMD is a
       Markdown editor with math (MathJax) support. What is special is
       that it keeps edit history. (Chinese UI.)
     * [https://www.penflip.com/]Penflip(Cloud): Penflip is designed to be
       a GitHub for writers. It is Markdown-based and git like without
       math support.
     * [https://www.authorea.com/]Authorea(Cloud): A much more powerful
       Markdown and LaTeX online editor that can be used to produce nice
       academic papers.
     * [http://dillinger.io/]Dillinger(Cloud): Markdown editor but no math
       mode.
     * [http://kramdown.herokuapp.com/]Online Kramdown Editor(Cloud): Just
       another Markdown editor without math support.
     * [http://pandoc.herokuapp.com/]Pandoc Markdown(Cloud): Just another
       Markdown editor with math (MathJax) support.
     * [http://marxi.co/]Marxico(Cloud,Mac,Win,Chrome): Markdown editor
       that integrates with Evernote, generates pdf and works offline.
       [https://maxiang.io/]¬¡(Cloud,Mac,Win,Chrome) is the Chinese
       version._
     * [https://www.madoko.net/]Madoko(Cloud,Chrome): A Markdown editor
       with math support, where images are inserted easily with one click,
       while your files are saved on Dropbox, GitHub, OneDrive or local
       disk. It generates pdf and HTML page and works offline using
       browser's local storage. One can even import LaTeX files.
     * [http://markx.herokuapp.com/]Markx(Cloud): Markdown editor for
       scientific writing. Batteries included.
     * [https://www.typora.io/]typora(Mac,Win): Beautiful UI and in-situ
       live preview.
     * [http://pad.haroopress.com/]Haroopad(Mac,Win,Linux): A powerful
       github flavored markdown editor with useful extensions. Math
       (mathjax) is supported.
     * [http://jbt.github.io/markdown-editor/]jbt/markdown-editor(Cloud):
       Just another online Markdown editor without math support.
     * [http://25.io/mou/]Mou(Mac): Mou used to be the best Markdown
       editor on Mac. It is not bad but DO NOT preorder Mou 1.0. This
       project is dead, unofficially.
       [http://matrix.sspai.com/p/c7a3c9c0]£º»,·»¤._
     * [http://markdownpad.com/]MarkdownPad (Win): If you have no bad
       feelings about .NET, this is pretty good.
     * [https://github.com/retext-project/retext]ReText (Mac,Win,Linux):
       ReText one of the best, even on Linux. It also supports
       reStructuredText input.
     * [https://www.madoko.net/]Madoko (Cloud): LaTeX × Markdown ²
     * [https://github.com/egoist/eme]eme (Win,Mac,Linux): Math support.
     * [https://moeditor.org/]Moeditor (Win,Mac,Linux): All purpose
       markdown editor.

   Notebook softwares that you can write in Markdown:
     * [https://boostnote.io/]boostnote (Win,Mac,Linux): Math + Markdown,
       with snippet note support.

LaTeX

     * [https://www.sharelatex.com/]ShareLaTeX(Cloud): Dropbox and GitHub
       integration, preview, cooperation, simple UI. It also provides a
       lot of templates.
     * [https://www.overleaf.com/]Overleaf(Cloud): Built in version
       control.
     * [https://www.authorea.com/]Authorea(Cloud): Easy to use UI.
       Supports both Markdown and LaTeX.
     * [https://www.papeeria.com/]Papeeria(Cloud): Just another online
       LaTeX and Markdown with plot compiler and collaborations.
     * [http://jaxedit.com/]JaxEdit(Cloud): JaxEdit doesn't provide full
       LaTeX support but is good enough for simple LaTeX documents and
       slides.

   You can also host one using your own machine.
     * [https://github.com/alabid/flylatex]FlyLaTeX: A free, open source
       version of sharelatex
     * [https://github.com/sharelatex/sharelatex]ShareLaTeX Source Code:
       ShareLaTeX open sourced their codes. This is a great move I would
       say.
     * [http://www.texstudio.org/]TeXStudio - Cross-platform LaTeX editor
       that stems from TeXMaker.
     * [http://www.winedt.com/]WinEdt - The LaTeX editor many people swear
       by.
     * [http://www.texniccenter.org/]TeXnicCenter - A quite old but free
       and decent editor for LaTeX.
     * [https://www.lyx.org/]LyX - Cross-platform WYSIWYM editor that uses
       LaTeX behind the scenes to render documents.
     * [http://pages.uoregon.edu/koch/texshop/]TeXshop - No-nonsense
       editor for LaTeX documents which is included in MacTeX.
     * [https://www.tug.org/texworks/]TeXWorks - No-nonsense editor for
       LaTeX code, modeled after TeXShop, but this one is cross-platform.

iPython Notebook

   Use IPython Notebook to help with your research. IPython Notebook can
   be previewed on GitHub directly. Here are some examples of how IPython
   notebook can be used.
     * [https://github.com/jrjohansson/scientific-python-lectures]Scientif
       ic Python Lectures
     * [http://reproduced-papers.github.io/]Reproduced Papers
     * [https://github.com/ipython/ipython/wiki/A-gallery-of-interesting-I
       Python-Notebooks]More: For more IPython notebook on GitHub please
       read this enormous list.

